<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="21.[189,310,1050,1076]" box="[189,310,1050,1076]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,310,1050,1076]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,310,1050,1076]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[189,1399,1097,1369]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
This species is recognized among species of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hwang &amp; Weirauch" authorityYear="2017" box="[733,926,1097,1123]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Breviphysoderes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[733,926,1097,1123]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Breviphysoderes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the head and anterior pronotal lobe being distinctly covered with dense, short, curved, setigerous tubercles, the deeply defined pronotal paramedian carina, the hemelytron surpassing the tip of the abdomen, the medial vein of the hemelytron shaped like an inverted 
<collectionCode box="[475,493,1203,1229]" country="Sweden" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15668" name="Department of Botany, Swedish Museum of Natural History" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="Herbarium">S</collectionCode>
, and the elongated external cell of the hemelytron (Cu + 
<collectionCode box="[1172,1202,1203,1229]" country="Germany" lsid="urn:lsid:biocol.org:col:15637" name="Botanische Staatssammlung München" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="Herbarium">M</collectionCode>
). This species is most similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Hwang &amp; Weirauch, 2017" authorityName="Hwang &amp; Weirauch" authorityYear="2017" box="[374,522,1238,1264]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Breviphysoderes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tenebrosa" status="gen. et sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[374,522,1238,1264]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">B. tenebrosa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[529,707,1238,1264]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" rank="species">gen. et sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hwang &amp; Weirauch" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Miller" baseAuthorityYear="1940" box="[764,921,1238,1264]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Breviphysoderes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="planicollis" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis box="[764,921,1238,1264]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">B. planicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[929,1059,1238,1264]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" rank="species">comb. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
It can be differentiated from the former by the overall coloration, the diverging antero-lateral pronotal projections, and the shape of the external cell. It differs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Hwang &amp; Weirauch" authorityYear="2017" baseAuthorityName="Miller" baseAuthorityYear="1940" box="[565,722,1308,1334]" class="Insecta" family="Reduviidae" genus="Breviphysoderes" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="planicollis" status="comb. nov.">
<emphasis box="[565,722,1308,1334]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">B. planicollis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[730,860,1308,1335]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" rank="species">comb. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
by the overall coloration and the shape of the external cell.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
